+# Continuation Token Pagination Design
+
+## Overview
+
+This document explains the cursor-based pagination implementation for the `listDAGExecutionIterationIds` API endpoint in the LiveTable service. The implementation provides efficient, stateless pagination for DAG execution history with support for nested DAGs across multiple folders.
+
+**Status**: ✅ Implemented and Validated
+
+---
+
+## Architecture
+
+### Component Flow
+
+```
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                      Client Application                         │
+│  - Sends historyCount + optional continuationToken              │
+│  - Reads x-ms-continuation-token from response header           │
+└────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
+                             │
+                             ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                  LiveTableController                            │
+│  - Receives request parameters                                  │
+│  - Calls handler to get (items, nextToken) tuple                │
+│  - Appends x-ms-continuation-token header if nextToken exists   │
+│  - Returns items array in response body                         │
+└────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
+                             │
+                             ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                    LiveTableHandler                             │
+│  - Passes through to DagExecutionStore                          │
+│  - Returns (List<DagExecutionIteration>, string?) tuple         │
+└────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
+                             │
+                             ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                   DagExecutionStore                             │
+│  - Passes through to persistence manager                        │
+│  - Returns (List<DagExecutionIteration>, string?) tuple         │
+└────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
+                             │
+                             ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│        FileSystemBasedDagExecutionPersistenceManager            │
+│  - Reads from multiple Index_StartTime_* folders                │
+│  - Aggregates and sorts globally                                │
+│  - Applies cursor filtering after aggregation                   │
+│  - Uses N+1 pattern to detect more pages                        │
+│  - Generates next continuation token                            │
+└────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
+                             │
+                             ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                ContinuationTokenHelper                          │
+│  - Encode(reverseEpoch, iterationId, status, filterHash)        │
+│  - TryDecode(token) → (reverseEpoch, iterationId, status, hash) │
+│  - ComputeFilterHash(statuses, startTime, endTime, mlvIds)      │
+│  - ValidateFilterHash(token, currentFilters)                    │
+└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
+```
+
+### File System Structure
+
+DAG execution metrics are stored across multiple folders for nested DAGs:
+
+```
+DagExecutionMetrics/
+├── Index_StartTime_{artifactId}/           ← Default/manual runs
+│   ├── 9223372036854775807_guid1_Succeeded_9223372036854775000
+│   ├── 9223372036854775806_guid2_Failed_9223372036854774999
+│   └── ...
+├── Index_StartTime_{mlvDefinitionId_1}/    ← Schedule 1 runs
+│   ├── 9223372036854775805_guid3_Succeeded_9223372036854774998
+│   └── ...
+├── Index_StartTime_{mlvDefinitionId_2}/    ← Schedule 2 runs
+│   ├── 9223372036854775804_guid4_Running_9223372036854774997
+│   └── ...
+└── ...
+```
+
+**File Naming Convention**:
+```
+{reverseEpoch}_{iterationId}_{status}_{endReverseEpoch}
+```
+
+This naming enables:
+- Lexicographic sorting = chronological ordering (newest first)
+- Cursor filtering on file names without reading metadata
+- Status filtering on file names
+
+---
+
+## API Contract
+
+### Request Format
+```
+GET /api/v1/workspaces/{workspaceId}/lakehouses/{artifactId}/liveTable/listDAGExecutionIterationIds
+    ?historyCount=25
+    &continuationToken=OTIyMzM3MjAzNTA4NDc0ODMxN18xMGQzZjFkOS1kNTAyLTQ4MzMtOWVkMS1mNWZiYjc1NDAzZWNfU2tpcHBlZF9iZTViZTY5Zg==
+```
+
+| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |
+|-----------|------|----------|-------------|
+| `historyCount` | int | Yes | Number of items per page (1-500, default 500) |
+| `continuationToken` | string | No | Token from previous response to get next page |
+
+### Response Format
+
+**Response Body** (unchanged for backward compatibility):
+```json
+[
+    {
+        "iterationId": "d0b80801-72fc-49eb-80d5-70f0b2cb18e1",
+        "startedAt": "2026-01-16T07:58:13Z",
+        "status": "Failed",
+        "displayName": "MyRun-2",
+        "mlvCount": -1,
+        "endedAt": "2026-01-16T07:58:13Z"
+    },
+    {
+        "iterationId": "3a83ea71-e305-443c-875b-ee722a5dc6f4",
+        "startedAt": "2026-01-16T07:57:15Z",
+        "status": "Succeeded",
+        "displayName": "NewRun1",
+        "mlvCount": 3,
+        "endedAt": "2026-01-16T07:57:45Z"
+    }
+]
+```
+
+**Response Header** (only when more pages exist):
+```
+x-ms-continuation-token: OTIyMzM3MjAzNTA4NDc0ODMxN18xMGQzZjFkOS1kNTAyLTQ4MzMtOWVkMS1mNWZiYjc1NDAzZWNfU2tpcHBlZF9iZTViZTY5Zg==
+```
+
+### Backward Compatibility
+
+✅ **Fully backward compatible**:
+- Response body format unchanged (plain JSON array)
+- Header only added when more results exist
+- Existing clients unaffected (can ignore header)
+- Invalid/malformed token returns 400: "Page data is no longer available. Please refresh to reload."
+
+---
+
+## Token Format
+
+### Structure
+
+```
+Unencoded: {reverseEpoch}_{iterationId}_{status}_{filterHash}
+Example:   9223372035508474831_10d3f1d9-d502-4833-9ed1-f5fbb75403ec_Skipped_be5be69f
+
+Encoded:   Base64Url(unencoded)
+Example:   OTIyMzM3MjAzNTA4NDc0ODMxN18xMGQzZjFkOS1kNTAyLTQ4MzMtOWVkMS1mNWZiYjc1NDAzZWNfU2tpcHBlZF9iZTViZTY5Zg
+```
+
+### Token Components
+
+| Component | Description | Purpose |
+|-----------|-------------|---------|
+| `reverseEpoch` | `long.MaxValue - UnixEpochSeconds(StartedAt)` | Primary cursor position (descending order) |
+| `iterationId` | GUID of last item | Secondary cursor (tie-breaker for same timestamps) |
+| `status` | Status of last item | Included for completeness |
+| `filterHash` | SHA256(filters)[0:16] | Detect filter changes between pages |
+
+### Why Reverse Epoch?
+
+Results are sorted **descending** (newest first). Using reverse epoch ensures:
+
+```
+Newer:  2026-02-05 → reverseEpoch: 9223372035508474831 (smaller)
+Older:  2026-02-04 → reverseEpoch: 9223372035508561231 (larger)
+```
+
+Lexicographic comparison of file names = chronological descending order.
+
+### Filter Hash
+
+Prevents inconsistent results when filters change between pages:
+
+```csharp
+// Hash computation
+var input = $"{string.Join(",", statuses)}|{startTime}|{endTime}|{string.Join(",", mlvIds)}";
+var hash = SHA256(input).Substring(0, 16); // First 16 chars
+
+// Validation on subsequent pages
+if (tokenHash != currentHash) {
+    // Filter changed - return 400
+    throw new ArgumentException("Search criteria have changed. Please refresh to see updated results.");
+}
+```
+
+---
+
+## End-to-End Multi-Folder Pipeline
+
+The complete flow from API request to response, showing how multiple folders are handled:
+
+```
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│  1. DISCOVER FOLDERS [EXISTING]                                     │
+│     List all Index_StartTime_* folders under DagExecutionMetrics/   │
+│     Result: [folder_artifact, folder_mlv1, folder_mlv2, ...]       │
+└─────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────┘
+                          │
+                          ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│  2. FETCH FROM EACH FOLDER (IN PARALLEL) [EXISTING structure]       │
+│                                                                     │
+│     For each folder, independently:                                 │
+│     ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐     │
+│     │ No cursor (page 1): [EXISTING, modified fetch limit]    │     │
+│     │   No status filter → ListAsync(folder, historyCount+1)  │     │
+│     │   Has status filter → ListAsync(folder, 5000)           │     │
+│     │                                                         │     │
+│     │ With cursor (page 2+): [NEW]                            │     │
+│     │   FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync(folder, cursor, status)    │     │
+│     │   → Pages through 5000-item batches                     │     │
+│     │   → Skips files before/at cursor                        │     │
+│     │   → Collects until historyCount+1 MATCHING files found  │     │
+│     └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘     │
+│                                                                     │
+│     Each folder returns: List<filePath> (bounded per folder)        │
+└─────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────┘
+                          │
+                          ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│  3. READ METADATA (IN PARALLEL, THROTTLED) [EXISTING]               │
+│                                                                     │
+│     For each file path from step 2:                                 │
+│     a. Parse file name → reverseEpoch, iterationId, status, endedAt│
+│     b. Apply status filter → skip non-matching (return null)        │
+│     c. Apply time range filter → skip out-of-range (return null)    │
+│     d. Read metadata (mlvCount, submitUser) from file content       │
+│     e. Return DagExecutionIteration or null                         │
+│                                                                     │
+│     Throttled by SemaphoreSlim(MaxParallelFileReads) across         │
+│     ALL folders to avoid overwhelming OneLake                       │
+│                                                                     │
+│     Each folder returns: List<DagExecutionIteration>                │
+└─────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────┘
+                          │
+                          ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│  4. AGGREGATE AND SORT GLOBALLY                                     │
+│                                                                     │
+│     a. Flatten all items from all folders into one list [EXISTING]  │
+│                                                                     │
+│     b. Sort globally: [EXISTING]                                    │
+│        OrderByDescending(StartedAt)                                 │
+│        .ThenByDescending(IterationId.ToString())                    │
+│                                                                     │
+│        This is critical because items from different folders have   │
+│        interleaved timestamps:                                      │
+│          Folder A: [T1, T3, T5]                                     │
+│          Folder B: [T2, T4, T6]                                     │
+│          Merged:   [T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6]                        │
+│                                                                     │
+│     c. Apply cursor filter AFTER global sort (safety net): [NEW]    │
+│        Skip items with reverseEpoch < cursor (already returned)     │
+│        Skip cursor item itself (exact match)                        │
+│        This catches any items that per-folder filtering missed      │
+│                                                                     │
+│     d. Take historyCount + 1 items (N+1 pattern) [NEW]             │
+│        If count > historyCount → more pages exist                   │
+│        Return first historyCount items + generate next token        │
+│        If count <= historyCount → last page, no token               │
+└─────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────┘
+                          │
+                          ▼
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│  5. RETURN RESPONSE [MODIFIED]                                      │
+│     Body: JSON array of DagExecutionIteration items [EXISTING]      │
+│     Header: x-ms-continuation-token (if more pages exist) [NEW]     │
+└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
+```
+
+### Why Per-Folder Fetch Is Safe With Multiple Folders
+
+Each folder is fetched independently with the **same cursor**. This works because:
+
+1. **Cursor is timestamp-based**: `reverseEpoch` from the globally-sorted last item. Every folder uses the same timestamp boundary.
+
+2. **Over-fetching is harmless**: If a folder returns items that were already returned (because they're newer than the cursor), the global cursor filter in step 4c removes them.
+
+3. **Under-fetching per folder is handled**: If one folder has no items after the cursor, it simply returns an empty list. Other folders contribute their items.
+
+4. **Global sort ensures correctness**: Even if per-folder results overlap or have gaps, the global sort + cursor filter + N+1 pattern produces the correct page.
+
+### Memory Profile With Multiple Folders
+
+```
+Given: 5 folders, historyCount=25, no status filter
+
+First page:
+  Per folder: 26 file paths in memory
+  Total: 5 × 26 = 130 file paths
+  After metadata read: 130 DagExecutionIteration objects
+  After aggregation: Take 26 → return 25
+
+Page 2+ (cursor at position ~25):
+  Per folder: FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync collects up to 26 files
+  Batch size: 5000 per ListWithContinuationAsync call
+  Most folders: cursor found in first batch, 26 files collected
+  Total: 5 × ~26 = ~130 file paths
+  After metadata + aggregation: Take 26 → return 25
+```
+
+---
+
+## Pagination Algorithm
+
+### First Page (No Token)
+
+```
+1. For each Index_StartTime_* folder (in parallel):
+   a. If status filter present:
+      List files (limited to MaxFetchPerFolder = 5000)
+      Do NOT truncate after fetch (need all for sparse matching)
+   b. If no status filter:
+      List files (limited to historyCount + 1)
+   c. For each file: ReadSingleIterationAsync()
+      - Parse file name -> reverseEpoch, iterationId, status, endedAt
+      - Apply status filter (skip non-matching)
+      - Apply time range filter (skip out-of-range)
+      - Read metadata from file content
+
+2. Aggregate all matching items from all folders
+
+3. Sort globally: OrderByDescending(StartedAt).ThenByDescending(IterationId)
+
+4. Take first (historyCount + 1) items
+
+5. If count > historyCount:
+   - Return first historyCount items
+   - Generate token from item[historyCount - 1]
+   - Set hasMore = true
+
+6. Return (items, nextToken)
+```
+
+### Subsequent Pages (With Token)
+
+```
+1. Decode and validate token
+   - If filter hash mismatch → return 400: "Search criteria have changed"
+
+2. For each Index_StartTime_* folder:
+   a. Call FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync(folder, cursor, historyCount, statusFilter):
+      - Page through files in 5000-item batches using ListWithContinuationAsync
+      - Skip files until cursor position is found
+      - Collect files after cursor
+      - Count only STATUS-MATCHING files toward threshold
+      - Stop early once historyCount+1 matching items found
+   b. For each file: ReadSingleIterationAsync() (status/time filter + metadata)
+   c. Result: only the matching items needed (memory-bounded)
+
+3. Aggregate filtered items from all folders
+
+4. Sort globally: OrderByDescending(StartedAt).ThenByDescending(IterationId)
+
+5. Apply cursor filter after global sort (safety net for multi-folder)
+
+6. Take first (historyCount + 1) items
+
+7. Generate next token if more items exist
+
+8. Return (items, nextToken)
+```
+
+### Why Cursor Filter After Aggregation?
+
+**Problem**: Items are distributed across multiple folders with interleaved timestamps.
+
+```
+Folder A: [T1, T3, T5, T7]
+Folder B: [T2, T4, T6, T8]
+Global order: [T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8]
+```
+
+If cursor is at T4 and we filter per-folder:
+- Folder A after T4: [T5, T7] ✓
+- Folder B after T4: [T6, T8] ✓
+
+But if we filter per-folder BEFORE knowing global order:
+- Folder A might skip items that should be included
+- Items get lost
+
+**Solution**: Aggregate first, then filter globally.
+
+### Visual Example: 3 Folders, historyCount=3
+
+```
+DagExecutionMetrics/
+├── Index_StartTime_artifact-id/
+│   ├── 9223372036854775807_iter-001_Running           (newest)
+│   ├── 9223372036854775757_iter-002_Completed_...
+│   └── 9223372036854775707_iter-003_Failed_...
+│
+├── Index_StartTime_mlv-def-1/
+│   ├── 9223372036854775787_iter-101_Completed_...
+│   └── 9223372036854775737_iter-102_Completed_...
+│
+└── Index_StartTime_mlv-def-2/
+    ├── 9223372036854775777_iter-201_Running
+    └── 9223372036854775727_iter-202_Completed_...
+```
+
+**Page 1 Request (no token)**:
+```
+1. List files from each folder
+2. Aggregate and sort by reverseEpoch ASC (= StartedAt DESC):
+   ...807(iter-001) → ...787(iter-101) → ...777(iter-201) → ...757(iter-002) → ...
+3. Take 4 items (historyCount + 1)
+   [iter-001, iter-101, iter-201, iter-002]
+4. count(4) > historyCount(3), so more pages exist
+   Return: [iter-001, iter-101, iter-201]
+   Token:  encode(reverseEpoch=...777, iterationId=iter-201)
+```
+
+**Page 2 Request (with token)**:
+```
+Token decoded: cursorReverseEpoch=...777, cursorIterationId=iter-201
+
+Cursor filtering (skip items already returned):
+- ...807 > ...777 → SKIP (newer, already returned)
+- ...787 > ...777 → SKIP (newer, already returned)  
+- ...777 == ...777 AND iter-201 == iter-201 → SKIP (cursor item)
+- ...757 < ...777 → KEEP
+- ...737 < ...777 → KEEP
+- ...727 < ...777 → KEEP
+- ...707 < ...777 → KEEP
+
+After filtering & sort:
+[iter-002, iter-102, iter-202, iter-003]
+
+Return: [iter-002, iter-102, iter-202]
+Token:  encode(reverseEpoch=...727, iterationId=iter-202)
+```
+
+### Cursor Filtering Logic
+
+```csharp
+// Skip items already returned (newer items have smaller reverseEpoch)
+bool ShouldIncludeItem(long reverseEpoch, Guid iterationId, 
+                       long cursorReverseEpoch, Guid cursorIterationId)
+{
+    // Skip if newer than cursor (already returned in previous page)
+    if (reverseEpoch < cursorReverseEpoch)
+        return false;
+    
+    // Skip the exact cursor item (last item from previous page)
+    if (reverseEpoch == cursorReverseEpoch && 
+        iterationId.ToString() == cursorIterationId.ToString())
+        return false;
+    
+    // Include - this item belongs to the next page
+    return true;
+}
+```
+
+**Key insight**: Filtering happens on **file names** (string parsing) **before** expensive metadata I/O.
+
+---
+
+## Design Challenges
+
+### Challenge 1: Unbounded File Listing on Subsequent Pages (CRITICAL)
+
+**Problem**: When a continuation token was provided, naively listing **ALL files** from each index folder (`fetchLimit = -1`) would be required because the cursor position could be anywhere in the sorted file list, and the code would need to find and skip past it.
+
+```csharp
+// DANGEROUS - Lists ALL files - unbounded memory usage
+else if (cursorReverseEpoch.HasValue)
+{
+    fetchLimit = -1;  // ❌ Lists ALL files - unbounded memory usage
+}
+```
+
+**Impact**: For long-lived artifacts with extensive execution history, this could cause:
+
+| Scenario | Files per Folder | Memory for Paths | Risk |
+|----------|------------------|------------------|------|
+| New artifact (< 1 year) | ~100-500 | ~50-100 KB | ✅ Safe |
+| Active artifact (1-3 years) | ~1,000-5,000 | ~500 KB-2 MB | ⚠️ Caution |
+| Long-lived artifact (3+ years) | ~10,000+ | ~5+ MB | ❌ OOM Risk |
+| Multiple MLV defs × deep pagination | Multiplied | ~50+ MB | ❌ Critical |
+
+**Root Cause**: The OneLake listing API returns files sorted lexicographically from the beginning. There's no "start at offset N" capability. To find items after a cursor at position 6000, you must first retrieve items 1-5999.
+
+### Challenge 2: Simple Cap Doesn't Work
+
+A naive fix of capping fetching at `MaxFetchPerFolder = 5000` doesn't work:
+
+```csharp
+// INCORRECT - Misses cursor if at position >5000
+else if (cursorReverseEpoch.HasValue)
+{
+    fetchLimit = MaxFetchPerFolder;  // ❌ Misses cursor if at position >5000
+}
+```
+
+**Why this fails**: If a folder has 10,000 files and the cursor is at position 6000:
+1. We fetch files 1-5000 (the 5000 newest)
+2. The cursor (at position 6000) is **NOT** in this batch
+3. All 5000 files have `reverseEpoch < cursorReverseEpoch` → all are skipped by cursor filtering
+4. **Result**: Returns 0 items, even though 4000 items exist after cursor
+
+### Challenge 3: Multi-Folder Interleaving
+
+Files are spread across multiple `Index_StartTime_*` folders. Items from different folders have interleaved timestamps, which means:
+- Per-folder cursor filtering is insufficient for correct global ordering
+- Each folder must return enough items to ensure correct results after global aggregation
+
+```
+Folder A: [T1, T3, T5, T7]    ← Timestamps interleave
+Folder B: [T2, T4, T6, T8]
+Global:   [T1, T2, T3, T4, T5, T6, T7, T8]
+```
+
+### Challenge 4: Azure SDK Page Boundary Tokens
+
+Azure SDK's `AsPages()` provides continuation tokens at **page boundaries**, not item boundaries. If a page returns more items than requested and we break early, the continuation token points to the next page, potentially skipping items within the current page.
+
+### Solution: Paged Cursor-Finding
+
+#### Core Idea
+
+Instead of loading all files into memory at once, page through files in bounded batches using the new `ListWithContinuationAsync` interface method. Skip batches until the cursor position is found, then collect only the items needed.
+
+#### New Interface: `ListWithContinuationAsync`
+
+Added to `IFileSystem.cs` to enable SDK-native storage pagination:
+
+```csharp
+Task<(List<string> Paths, string ContinuationToken)> ListWithContinuationAsync(
+    string path,
+    int maxCount = default,           // Defaults to 5000
+    string continuationToken = null,   // Resume from previous page
+    CancellationToken cancellationToken = default);
+```
+
+**Implementation** (`OnelakeBasedFileSystem.cs`): Uses Azure SDK's `AsPages()` method which natively supports continuation tokens for efficient directory listing.
+
+#### New Helper: `FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync`
+
+This method replaces the unbounded `fetchLimit = -1` approach:
+
+```
+FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync(fs, folder, cursorReverseEpoch, cursorIterationId, historyCount):
+    filesAfterCursor = []
+    storageToken = null
+    cursorFound = false
+    neededCount = historyCount + 1
+
+    do:
+        (batch, nextToken) = fs.ListWithContinuationAsync(folder, 5000, storageToken)
+
+        for each file in batch:
+            parse reverseEpoch, iterationId from filename
+
+            if not cursorFound:
+                if file is before cursor → skip
+                if file is cursor item → skip
+                if file is after cursor → cursorFound = true
+
+            if cursorFound:
+                add file to filesAfterCursor
+                if filesAfterCursor.count >= neededCount → return
+
+        storageToken = nextToken
+    while storageToken != null
+
+    return filesAfterCursor
+```
+
+#### Fetch Strategy Summary
+
+```
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                    Fetch Strategy (Basics)                    │
+├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
+│                                                             │
+│  historyCount <= 0?  ──YES──▶  fetchLimit = -1 (all)       │
+│         │                                                   │
+│         NO                                                  │
+│         │                                                   │
+│  Has cursor?  ──YES──▶  FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync()       │
+│         │                 ├─ Pages in 5000-item batches     │
+│         NO                ├─ Skips until cursor found       │
+│         │                 ├─ Collects historyCount+1 items  │
+│         ▼                 └─ Max 5000 items in memory       │
+│  fetchLimit =                                               │
+│  historyCount + 1                                           │
+│  (first page only)                                          │
+│                                                             │
+└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
+```
+
+#### Memory Comparison: Unbounded vs Paged
+
+| Scenario | Unbounded Approach | Paged Approach |
+|----------|----------------|------------|
+| 100 files, cursor at 50 | 100 paths in memory | ≤ 100 paths (1 batch) |
+| 10,000 files, cursor at 5,000 | 10,000 paths in memory | ≤ 5,000 paths per batch |
+| 100,000 files, cursor at 50,000 | ❌ 100,000 paths in memory | ≤ 5,000 paths per batch |
+| 100,000 files, cursor at 99,000 | ❌ 100,000 paths in memory | ≤ 5,000 paths per batch |
+
+#### MaxFetchPerFolder Constant
+
+```csharp
+private const int MaxFetchPerFolder = 5000;
+```
+
+Aligned with ecosystem defaults:
+- `workload-lakehouse/OneLakeClient.cs`: `DefaultMaxResultsForListPaths = 5000`
+- `workload-fabriclivetable/OneLakeRestClient.cs`: `DefaultMaxResultsForListPaths = 5000`
+- Azure DataLake Storage REST API: `maxResults` parameter max is 5000
+
+---
+
+## Status Filter Challenge & Solution
+
+### Problem
+
+When a status filter is applied (e.g., `status=Skipped`), matching files may be **sparse** — scattered among many non-matching files. A naive fetch strategy that fetches only `historyCount+1` files per folder on the first page, and counts **raw files** (not status-matching files) in `FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync` on subsequent pages, causes **underfetch**:
+
+```
+Folder contents (300 files, only 30 are Skipped):
+  [Completed, Skipped, Completed, Completed, Completed, Skipped, ...]
+   ^^^^^^^^^                                              ^^^^^^^
+   Only 10% match the status filter
+
+With historyCount=5 (first page):
+  Fetch 6 files → maybe 0-1 Skipped items → page looks empty
+  
+With cursor (page 2+):
+  FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync collects 6 raw files after cursor
+  → maybe 0-1 Skipped → not enough items → pagination stops early
+```
+
+**Impact**: Paginated results return **fewer items** than non-paginated baseline. For example, baseline returns 30 Skipped items but pagination returns only 20.
+
+### Root Cause (Two Locations)
+
+1. **First page** (`else` branch in `ReadIterationsFromSingleFolderAsync`):
+   - Fetches `historyCount+1` files per folder
+   - Then truncates to `historyCount+1` again after cursor filtering
+   - Status filtering happens **later** in `ReadSingleIterationAsync` → too few matching items
+
+2. **Page 2+** (`FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync`):
+   - Counts **all files** after cursor toward `neededCount` threshold
+   - Stops after collecting `historyCount+1` raw files
+   - Status filtering happens later → sparse matches mean insufficient results
+
+### First Page — Fetch More Files When Status Filter Present
+
+```csharp
+// When status filter is present, fetch MaxFetchPerFolder to ensure enough matching items
+bool hasStatusFilter = filters.Statuses?.Count > 0;
+int fetchLimit = hasStatusFilter ? MaxFetchPerFolder : historyCount + 1;
+```
+
+When status filters are present, we intentionally over-fetch to ensure enough matching items survive the later status filtering step.
+
+### First Page — Skip Post-Fetch Truncation With Status Filter
+
+After fetching, there is a truncation step that cuts `filteredFilePaths` back to `historyCount+1`. This is skipped when status filters are present to preserve the over-fetched results:
+
+```csharp
+// Skip truncation when status filter present to keep enough matching items
+bool hasStatusFilter = filters.Statuses?.Count > 0;
+if (!hasStatusFilter && historyCount > 0 && indexFilePaths.Count > (historyCount + 1))
+    filteredFilePaths = indexFilePaths.Take(historyCount + 1).ToList();
+```
+
+### Page 2+ — Status-Aware Counting in `FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync`
+
+The method accepts `statusFilter` and counts only **matching** files toward the threshold:
+
+```csharp
+// Count only status-matching files toward the threshold
+filesAfterCursor.Add(filePath);
+if (statusSet == null || statusSet.Contains(status))
+    matchingCount++;
+if (matchingCount >= neededCount)
+    return filesAfterCursor;
+```
+
+Status is extracted from the file name using `ValidateIndexFileName` — no additional I/O needed since the status is encoded in the file name convention `{reverseEpoch}_{iterationId}_{status}_{endEpoch}`.
+
+### Fetch Strategy Summary
+
+```
+┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                    Fetch Strategy                                 │
+├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
+│                                                                  │
+│  historyCount <= 0?  ──YES──▶  fetchLimit = -1 (all)            │
+│         │                                                        │
+│         NO                                                       │
+│         │                                                        │
+│  Has cursor?  ──YES──▶  FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync()            │
+│         │                 ├─ Pages in 5000-item batches          │
+│         NO                ├─ Skips until cursor found            │
+│         │                 ├─ Counts only STATUS-MATCHING files   │
+│         ▼                 └─ Stops at historyCount+1 matches     │
+│                                                                  │
+│  Has status filter?                                              │
+│    YES → fetchLimit = MaxFetchPerFolder (5000)                   │
+│           + skip post-fetch truncation                           │
+│    NO  → fetchLimit = historyCount + 1                           │
+│           + truncate to historyCount + 1                         │
+│                                                                  │
+└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
+```
+
+---
+
+## Performance Optimization
+
+### Challenge: Large Datasets
+
+With 3 schedules/minute × 30 days = 129,600 files
+
+Naive approach (fetch all then paginate) is too slow and can cause OOM.
+
+### Optimization Strategy
+
+| Phase | First Page | Subsequent Pages |
+|-------|------------|----------------------|
+| File Listing | Limited (historyCount + 1) | Paged via `ListWithContinuationAsync` (5000/batch) |
+| Cursor Finding | N/A | Stream through batches, skip until cursor found |
+| Items Collected | historyCount + 1 | historyCount + 1 (stop early once found) |
+| Max Memory | historyCount + 1 paths | 5000 paths per batch |
+
+### Why Paged Cursor-Finding is Better Than Unbounded Fetch
+
+| Aspect | Unbounded Fetch | Paged Cursor-Finding |
+|--------|----------------|---------------------------|
+| File listing | `fetchLimit = -1` (all at once) | Batches of 5000 via SDK pagination |
+| Memory usage | O(n) where n = total files | O(min(5000, remaining files)) |
+| Correctness | ✅ Always correct | ✅ Always correct |
+| Cursor at position 50,000 | ❌ 50K+ strings in memory | ✅ Max 5K per batch, 10 batches |
+| First page | ✅ Optimized | ✅ Same (no change) |
+
+### Why This Works
+
+1. **File listing is cheap** - Only reads file names, not content
+2. **Cursor filtering on names is fast** - String comparison in memory
+3. **Metadata reads are expensive** - Limited to what's needed
+4. **First page is fastest** - No need to find cursor position
+
+### Measured Performance
+
+| Operation | Time |
+|-----------|------|
+| Single request (200 items) | ~2.8 sec |
+| First page (10 items) | ~1.7 sec |
+| Subsequent page (10 items) | ~1.7 sec avg |
+
+### Complexity Analysis
+
+| Aspect | Complexity |
+|--------|------------|
+| File listing | O(n) where n = files in folder |
+| Cursor filtering | O(n) string parsing, no I/O |
+| Metadata reads | O(historyCount × numFolders) |
+| Aggregation/sort | O(m log m) where m = total items |
+| Memory | O(historyCount × numFolders) |
+
+---
+
+## Edge Cases Handled
+
+### 1. Same-Timestamp Items
+
+**Problem**: Multiple items with identical `StartedAt` could appear in random order.
+
+**Solution**: Secondary sort by `IterationId.ToString()` descending.
+
+```csharp
+.OrderByDescending(x => x.StartedAt)
+.ThenByDescending(x => x.IterationId.ToString())
+```
+
+### 2. Filter Changes Between Pages
+
+**Problem**: User changes status filter mid-pagination.
+
+**Solution**: Filter hash in token. Mismatch → return 400: "Search criteria have changed. Please refresh to see updated results."
+
+### 3. Invalid/Malformed Token
+
+**Problem**: Corrupted or tampered token.
+
+**Solution**: Return 400: "Page data is no longer available. Please refresh to reload."
+
+### 4. Concurrent Data Changes
+
+**Problem**: New items added while paginating.
+
+**Solution**: Cursor-based (not offset-based). New items with newer timestamps appear on page 1, not affecting current pagination position.
+
+### 5. Empty Results
+
+**Problem**: No items match filters.
+
+**Solution**: Return empty array `[]` with no continuation header.
+
+### 6. Cursor Scan Safety Limits
+
+**Problem**: `FetchFilesAfterCursorAsync` could loop infinitely (empty batches with non-null continuation tokens) or accumulate unbounded memory (sparse status filter across millions of files).
+
+**Solution**: `MaxCursorScanBatches = 200` constant caps scanning at 200 × 5,000 = **1M files per folder**.
+
+| Constant | Value | Purpose |
+|----------|-------|---------|
+| `MaxFetchPerFolder` | 5,000 | Max files per storage batch (aligned with OneLake default) |
+| `MaxCursorScanBatches` | 200 | Max batches scanned when seeking cursor position |
+| **Max files scanned** | **1,000,000** | Prevents infinite loops and bounds memory usage |
+
+When status filter is active, only matching files are accumulated — non-matching files are skipped entirely. At the batch limit, a warning is logged and the page returns whatever items were found (graceful degradation, no error).
+
