+## Design Decisions
+
+### Why Header-Only Token?
+
+✅ **Advantages:**
+- Response body unchanged (backward compatible)
+- Standard HTTP practice (metadata in headers)
+- Cleaner OpenAPI documentation
+- No envelope wrapper needed
+
+### Why Cursor-Based (Not Offset)?
+
+✅ **Advantages:**
+- Stable with concurrent data changes
+- No "skipped items" when new data arrives
+- Efficient with file-based storage (can filter on file names)
+
+### Why Filter Hash (Not Full Filter in Token)?
+
+✅ **Advantages:**
+- Smaller token size
+- Privacy (filters not exposed in token)
+- Simple validation (hash comparison)
+
+### Why Paged Cursor-Finding (Not Hard Cap)?
+
+✅ **Advantages:**
+- Memory-safe regardless of cursor position
+- Correct for any folder size (no silent data loss)
+- Leverages Azure SDK's native pagination
+- Early termination once enough items found
+
+---
+
+## Design Alternatives Considered
+
+### Option A: Hard Cap at 5000
+
+**Description**: Cap `fetchLimit` at 5000 when cursor is present.
+
+```csharp
+fetchLimit = MaxFetchPerFolder; // 5000
+```
+
+| Aspect | Assessment |
+|--------|-----------|
+| Memory safety | ✅ Bounded at 5000 |
+| Correctness | ❌ Fails if cursor is at position >5000 |
+| Complexity | ✅ Minimal (~2 lines) |
+
+**Rejected**: Incorrect behavior for long-lived artifacts where cursor could be deep in the list.
+
+### Option B1: Paged Cursor-Finding via `ListWithContinuationAsync` ← CHOSEN
+
+**Description**: Page through files in 5000-item batches using SDK-native continuation tokens until cursor is found.
+
+| Aspect | Assessment |
+|--------|-----------|
+| Memory safety | ✅ Max 5000 paths per batch |
+| Correctness | ✅ Always finds cursor regardless of position |
+| Complexity | Medium (~90 lines new code) |
+| Interface change | Yes - adds `ListWithContinuationAsync` to `IFileSystem` |
+
+**Chosen**: Best balance of memory safety and correctness.
+
+### Option B2: Per-Folder SDK Continuation Tokens in Cursor
+
+**Description**: Store OneLake continuation tokens (one per folder) inside the pagination cursor token.
+
+| Aspect | Assessment |
+|--------|-----------|
+| Memory safety | ✅ Each folder fetches only 1 page |
+| Correctness | ⚠️ Complex - requires tracking per-folder state |
+| Complexity | High - multi-folder token management |
+| Token size | ❌ Large (opaque SDK tokens × N folders) |
+
+**Rejected**: Over-engineered for current needs. Token size grows with folder count.
+
+### Option C: Unbounded Fetch
+
+**Description**: List ALL files when cursor is present (`fetchLimit = -1`).
+
+| Aspect | Assessment |
+|--------|-----------|
+| Memory safety | ❌ Unbounded - scales with folder size |
+| Correctness | ✅ Always correct |
+| Complexity | ✅ Simplest |
+
+**Rejected**: OOM risk for long-lived artifacts.
+
